  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "Passive Participle (اسم المفعول)",
      "titleArabic": "اسم المفعول",
      "content": [
        "The passive participle (اسم المفعول) is a noun derived from a verb that describes something that has had the action done to it. For Form I verbs (فَعَلَ), the pattern is مَفْعُول.",
        "Passive participles describe the result or state of having undergone an action."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Form I pattern: مَفْعُولٌ (e.g., مَكْتُوب from كَتَبَ)",
        "Feminine form: مَفْعُولَة (e.g., مَكْتُوبَة)",
        "Describes the receiver of the action, not the doer",
        "Often translates as the English '-ed' form"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "مَكْتُوبٌ", "english": "written" },
        { "arabic": "مَفْتُوحٌ", "english": "opened" },
        { "arabic": "مُغْلَقٌ", "english": "closed" },
        { "arabic": "مَكْسُورٌ", "english": "broken" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Difference Between Active and Passive Participles",
      "titleArabic": "الفرق بين اسم الفاعل واسم المفعول",
      "content": [
        "The active participle describes the doer, while the passive participle describes the object that received the action."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "كَاتِبٌ (active) = writer / one who writes",
        "مَكْتُوبٌ (passive) = written / that which is written",
        "فَاتِحٌ (active) = opener / one who opens",
        "مَفْتُوحٌ (passive) = opened / that which is opened"
      ]
    }
  ],
